1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,474
The police can take your car, your cash, even your house — and never

2
00:00:04,474 --> 00:00:06,119
charge you with a crime .

3
00:00:06,119 --> 00:00:09,541
They do it by accusing the property itself, not you.

4
00:00:09,541 --> 00:00:14,410
For decades, in much of the country, there was almost no limit on how much

5
00:00:14,410 --> 00:00:15,660
they could take.

6
00:00:15,660 --> 00:00:20,200
Then, in 2019, one man's Land Rover — seized over a small drug case —

7
00:00:20,200 --> 00:00:23,885
carried that question all the way to the Supreme Court .

8
00:00:23,885 --> 00:00:26,517
This is the case that finally drew a line .

9
00:00:26,867 --> 00:00:31,382
It is called civil asset forfeiture, and most people have never heard of

10
00:00:31,382 --> 00:00:33,138
it until it happens to them.

11
00:00:33,138 --> 00:00:36,524
It is not a fine handed down by a judge after a trial.

12
00:00:36,524 --> 00:00:41,102
It is the government taking your property because it claims that property

13
00:00:41,102 --> 00:00:45,303
was connected to a crime — sometimes without ever convicting you of

14
00:00:45,303 --> 00:00:46,553
anything .

15
00:00:46,553 --> 00:00:51,131
Over the next twelve minutes: how that system works, the man whose seized

16
00:00:51,131 --> 00:00:55,395
SUV exposed its limits, and the centuries-old rule the Supreme Court

17
00:00:55,395 --> 00:00:57,657
reached for to put the first real brake on it.

18
00:01:03,300 --> 00:01:06,868
His name is Tyson Timbs, and his story starts with a loss.

19
00:01:06,868 --> 00:01:10,990
When his father dies, Timbs receives roughly seventy-three thousand

20
00:01:10,990 --> 00:01:12,959
dollars in life-insurance money.

21
00:01:12,959 --> 00:01:17,142
With part of it, he buys a Land Rover SUV — about forty-two thousand

22
00:01:17,142 --> 00:01:17,696
dollars .

23
00:01:23,300 --> 00:01:24,738
He is also struggling.

24
00:01:24,738 --> 00:01:29,508
Prescribed opioids for pain, he becomes addicted, and the addiction pulls

25
00:01:29,508 --> 00:01:30,758
him toward heroin .

26
00:01:30,758 --> 00:01:35,463
To feed it, he sells a small amount of heroin to undercover officers — a

27
00:01:35,463 --> 00:01:37,227
few hundred dollars' worth.

28
00:01:37,227 --> 00:01:40,429
He is arrested, and he does not fight the charge.

29
00:01:40,429 --> 00:01:41,597
He pleads guilty .

30
00:01:46,600 --> 00:01:49,817
Now notice what the court does with him as a person.

31
00:01:49,817 --> 00:01:51,363
He is not sent to prison.

32
00:01:51,363 --> 00:01:55,632
He is sentenced to home detention and probation, plus a little over a

33
00:01:55,632 --> 00:01:57,241
thousand dollars in fees .

34
00:01:57,241 --> 00:02:01,818
The system has looked at Tyson Timbs, weighed his crime, and decided he is

35
00:02:01,818 --> 00:02:03,365
not someone to lock away.

36
00:02:11,800 --> 00:02:13,477
But the state is not finished.

37
00:02:13,477 --> 00:02:16,216
Separately, it moves to take the Land Rover — the

38
00:02:16,216 --> 00:02:20,297
forty-two-thousand-dollar SUV he bought with his father's insurance money

39
00:02:20,297 --> 00:02:21,547
.

40
00:02:21,547 --> 00:02:24,286
And here is the number that makes the whole case.

41
00:02:24,286 --> 00:02:28,143
The most Timbs could have been fined for his offense was ten thousand

42
00:02:28,143 --> 00:02:29,393
dollars .

43
00:02:29,393 --> 00:02:29,912
The car was worth more than four times that.

44
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:45,600
So a man who gets no prison time, for a small drug sale, stands to lose a

45
00:02:45,600 --> 00:02:49,590
vehicle worth quadruple the maximum fine the law allows.

46
00:02:49,590 --> 00:02:54,648
The trial court looks at that gap and says no — taking the car would be

47
00:02:54,648 --> 00:02:58,138
grossly disproportionate to what he actually did.

48
00:02:58,138 --> 00:03:01,344
It is, in plain terms, an excessive penalty .

49
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,101
That should have been the end of it.

50
00:03:09,101 --> 00:03:10,619
It was only the beginning.

51
00:03:10,619 --> 00:03:14,588
Because to take the car, the state was not really using the ordinary

52
00:03:14,588 --> 00:03:15,838
criminal law at all.

53
00:03:15,838 --> 00:03:19,725
It was using a separate, far older, and much stranger kind of power.

54
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:31,600
Civil asset forfeiture works on a legal fiction that sounds almost absurd

55
00:03:31,600 --> 00:03:32,892
when you first hear it.

56
00:03:32,892 --> 00:03:35,307
The case is not brought against the person.

57
00:03:35,307 --> 00:03:37,160
It is brought against the thing .

58
00:03:42,300 --> 00:03:46,926
That is why forfeiture cases have such peculiar names — the government

59
00:03:46,926 --> 00:03:50,297
versus a car, versus a sum of cash, versus a house.

60
00:03:50,297 --> 00:03:54,923
In the eyes of the law, the property itself is treated as the suspect.

61
00:03:54,923 --> 00:03:59,616
And because the case targets the object, not the owner, the protections

62
00:03:59,616 --> 00:04:03,185
you would expect in a criminal trial do not all apply.

63
00:04:03,185 --> 00:04:08,076
In many places, the owner does not have to be convicted of a crime to lose

64
00:04:08,076 --> 00:04:09,326
the property.

65
00:04:09,326 --> 00:04:11,975
In some, they do not even have to be charged .

66
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:25,392
Think about what that means.

67
00:04:25,392 --> 00:04:29,501
The whole weight of "innocent until proven guilty" is built around a

68
00:04:29,501 --> 00:04:30,751
person.

69
00:04:30,751 --> 00:04:34,335
Aim the case at an object instead, and that weight can quietly slip away.

70
00:04:38,900 --> 00:04:41,645
Now, there is a reason this power exists.

71
00:04:41,645 --> 00:04:46,532
Forfeiture grew as a tool to strip the profits out of organized crime and

72
00:04:46,532 --> 00:04:51,353
drug trafficking — to take the boats, the planes, the cash that made the

73
00:04:51,353 --> 00:04:52,603
crime worth doing.

74
00:04:52,603 --> 00:04:57,557
Used that way, supporters argue, it disrupts criminal enterprises in a way

75
00:04:57,557 --> 00:05:00,123
that arresting one person never could .

76
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:09,484
But critics point to what happens next, after the property is taken.

77
00:05:09,484 --> 00:05:13,820
In many state systems, and in a federal program, the proceeds flow back to

78
00:05:13,820 --> 00:05:16,398
the very agencies that seized the property .

79
00:05:16,398 --> 00:05:20,616
The department that takes your car can, in effect, help fund itself with

80
00:05:20,616 --> 00:05:21,866
it.

81
00:05:21,866 --> 00:05:26,143
The Institute for Justice, the firm that took up Timbs's case, calls this

82
00:05:26,143 --> 00:05:29,463
"policing for profit" — a built-in incentive to seize, regardless of guilt

83
00:05:29,463 --> 00:05:29,463
.

84
00:05:39,800 --> 00:05:42,035
This is not a left-or-right complaint.

85
00:05:42,035 --> 00:05:46,151
Criticism of civil forfeiture runs across the political spectrum, from

86
00:05:46,151 --> 00:05:50,326
civil-liberties groups to conservative reform groups, which is rare for

87
00:05:50,326 --> 00:05:51,914
any issue in American law .

88
00:05:51,914 --> 00:05:56,207
And yet, for years, one constitutional argument against it kept hitting a

89
00:05:56,207 --> 00:05:59,676
wall — the very wall Tyson Timbs's case was about to break.

90
00:06:06,900 --> 00:06:08,455
The argument was simple.

91
00:06:08,455 --> 00:06:12,991
The Eighth Amendment to the Constitution forbids "excessive fines." If

92
00:06:12,991 --> 00:06:16,684
taking a forty-two-thousand-dollar car for a crime with a

93
00:06:16,684 --> 00:06:20,507
ten-thousand-dollar maximum fine is not excessive, what is?

94
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,219
The protection against excessive fines is one of the oldest in our legal

95
00:06:28,219 --> 00:06:29,469
tradition.

96
00:06:29,469 --> 00:06:33,689
Its roots reach back centuries, through English law all the way to Magna

97
00:06:33,689 --> 00:06:37,733
Carta, which limited how harshly the crown could fine a person for an

98
00:06:37,733 --> 00:06:38,983
offense.

99
00:06:38,983 --> 00:06:43,144
The Supreme Court treated this as a right deeply rooted in the nation's

100
00:06:43,144 --> 00:06:43,691
history — not a modern invention .

101
00:06:52,100 --> 00:06:56,457
But there was a catch, and it is a technical one that decided everything.

102
00:06:56,457 --> 00:07:00,515
For most of American history, the Bill of Rights restrained only the

103
00:07:00,515 --> 00:07:01,765
federal government.

104
00:07:01,765 --> 00:07:05,704
Over the twentieth century, the Court "incorporated" most of those

105
00:07:05,704 --> 00:07:09,584
protections — applied them to the states, one by one, through the

106
00:07:09,584 --> 00:07:10,837
Fourteenth Amendment.

107
00:07:10,837 --> 00:07:15,254
The question in Timbs was whether the ban on excessive fines had ever been

108
00:07:15,254 --> 00:07:17,522
formally applied to the states at all.

109
00:07:17,522 --> 00:07:21,819
Indiana's Supreme Court had said no — and used that gap to uphold taking

110
00:07:21,819 --> 00:07:22,240
the car .

111
00:07:33,500 --> 00:07:36,328
In 2019, the Supreme Court closed the gap.

112
00:07:36,328 --> 00:07:41,175
By a unanimous vote — nine to nothing — it held that the Excessive Fines

113
00:07:41,175 --> 00:07:44,744
Clause does apply to the states, just like the rest .

114
00:07:44,744 --> 00:07:48,447
The opinion was written by Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg.

115
00:07:48,447 --> 00:07:53,361
A protection that old, she reasoned, that fundamental, could not possibly

116
00:07:53,361 --> 00:07:58,209
bind only the federal government while leaving every state and city free

117
00:07:58,209 --> 00:08:00,296
to impose fines without limit .

118
00:08:05,400 --> 00:08:09,246
The justices were so united that the only disagreement was about the

119
00:08:09,246 --> 00:08:10,496
route, not the result.

120
00:08:10,496 --> 00:08:14,569
Justices Gorsuch and Thomas agreed the clause applies to the states, but

121
00:08:14,569 --> 00:08:18,472
argued it should get there through a different part of the Fourteenth

122
00:08:18,472 --> 00:08:19,722
Amendment .

123
00:08:19,722 --> 00:08:21,747
On the core point, there was no dissent at all.

124
00:08:29,700 --> 00:08:33,532
But read the ruling carefully, because the Court was careful.

125
00:08:33,532 --> 00:08:37,553
It did not declare that taking Timbs's car was unconstitutional.

126
00:08:37,553 --> 00:08:39,877
It did not abolish civil forfeiture .

127
00:08:39,877 --> 00:08:44,338
It did something narrower and, in a way, more durable: it sent the case

128
00:08:44,338 --> 00:08:48,672
back to Indiana and held that, from now on, the question of whether a

129
00:08:48,672 --> 00:08:53,007
forfeiture is an excessive fine is a real constitutional question the

130
00:08:53,007 --> 00:08:54,452
states have to answer .

131
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:04,632
So Timbs is a limit, not an ending.

132
00:09:04,632 --> 00:09:06,460
Civil forfeiture still exists.

133
00:09:06,460 --> 00:09:08,410
Police can still seize property.

134
00:09:08,410 --> 00:09:12,796
What changed is that there is now a constitutional ceiling — a principle

135
00:09:12,796 --> 00:09:16,939
that the punishment, including the value of what is taken, cannot be

136
00:09:16,939 --> 00:09:21,386
grossly out of proportion to the offense, in any courtroom in the country

137
00:09:21,386 --> 00:09:21,447
.

138
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:33,010
And for Tyson Timbs himself, the story has an ending most of these cases

139
00:09:33,010 --> 00:09:34,260
never get.

140
00:09:34,260 --> 00:09:38,936
Back in Indiana, after years of litigation, the courts finally applied

141
00:09:38,936 --> 00:09:41,675
that principle and let him keep his car .

142
00:09:41,675 --> 00:09:45,569
The Land Rover his father's death had paid for stayed in his hands.

143
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:52,942
But step back from the one car.

144
00:09:52,942 --> 00:09:55,134
The deeper power has not gone away.

145
00:09:55,134 --> 00:09:59,582
Every day, property is seized across the country on the theory that the

146
00:09:59,582 --> 00:10:02,150
object, not the owner, is the wrongdoer .

147
00:10:02,150 --> 00:10:06,535
Timbs gave people a tool — a way to argue that a seizure is simply too

148
00:10:06,535 --> 00:10:10,983
much — but you have to know the tool exists, and you have to be able to

149
00:10:10,983 --> 00:10:12,612
fight for years to use it.

150
00:10:12,612 --> 00:10:13,802
Most people cannot.

151
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:28,633
That is the quiet truth under the case.

152
00:10:28,633 --> 00:10:33,125
A constitutional limit is only as strong as the people who can afford to

153
00:10:33,125 --> 00:10:34,375
invoke it.

154
00:10:34,375 --> 00:10:35,625
The line exists now.

155
00:10:35,625 --> 00:10:38,739
Whether it protects you depends on whether you can reach it.

156
00:10:44,800 --> 00:10:49,196
We have spent three episodes on what the state can see of you — your

157
00:10:49,196 --> 00:10:51,459
street, your phone, your movements.

158
00:10:51,459 --> 00:10:53,334
This is a different question.

159
00:10:53,334 --> 00:10:56,501
Not what they can watch, but what they can take .

160
00:10:56,501 --> 00:11:01,156
And Timbs is the moment the Court said that even here, where the case is

161
00:11:01,156 --> 00:11:05,811
aimed at a thing instead of a person, there is a line that a fine — or a

162
00:11:05,811 --> 00:11:07,556
forfeiture — cannot cross .

163
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:22,383
It took a man, a Land Rover, and a rule older than the country to draw it.

164
00:11:25,700 --> 00:11:28,854
But property is not only what you can carry or drive.

165
00:11:28,854 --> 00:11:33,199
What happens when the thing the government wants is the ground under your

166
00:11:33,199 --> 00:11:37,068
feet — your home — and it wants to hand that home to someone else

167
00:11:37,068 --> 00:11:38,318
entirely?

168
00:11:38,318 --> 00:11:42,722
The Constitution says the government can take private property for "public

169
00:11:42,722 --> 00:11:47,066
use." The next case asked the most dangerous question hiding in those two

170
00:11:47,066 --> 00:11:48,316
words: what counts as public use?

171
00:11:58,100 --> 00:11:59,307
That is next time.
